Serial Measurement Analysis

Patrick Ward

6/2/2023

Intro

In the applied setting we often deal with longotudinal data collected on an athlete over time (serial measurement). Consequently, this is a bit different of a testing environment than the traditional test-retest type of analysis that is conducted under more controlled settings (and used for subsequent reliability analysis). While we can (and should) conduct test-retest analysis of the testing procedures we utilize, in order to explore the systematic and unsystematic error of the test (in a controlled environment), we should also be mindful that the week-to-week variance that an athlete may display in a test throughout a competitive season may not be adequately reflected in the test-retest trial (e.g., there might be more variation in weekly testing due to a number of different factors that can influence an athletes performance during the competitive season – injury, psychological mood, fatigue, etc.). As such, practitioners may benefit from complimenting their test-retest reliability studies with alternative methods for exploring week-to-week change. Additionally, in the applied setting (especially at the elite level) conducting a test-retest trial may be challenging given scheduling constraints and athlete compliance. Thus, establishing weekly variance and meaningful change values utilizing serial measurements may be more advantageous for this situation.

The goal of this tutorial is to evaluate serial counter movement jump height, across a season, for NFL football players and provide a few different approaches to exploring weekly variance and determining if a change is outside of the “norm” and worth discussing among the performance staff and perhaps creating an intervention for.

Test-Retest Analysis

Before delving into measuring variance in serial measurement, let’s start with a test-retest analysis. Here, we will operate as if the first two tests represent the test-retest trials we care about. Generally, these two tests are taken in the early season (one test at pre-season physical testing day and the second test a week later).

Start by getting the first two tests for each player

test_retest <- df %>%
  group_by(player_id) %>%
  filter(n() <= 2) %>%
  mutate(test_num = row_number()) %>%
  ungroup()

Plot the test results for each athlete

test_retest %>%
  group_by(player_id) %>%

Variance

An athlete’s true score is a representation of their observed score plus some level of error.

\(Y_i = n + e_i\)

The variance for observed scores can calculated as:

\(sigma^2(Y_i) = sigma^2(n) + sigma^2(e)\)

Where: * sigma^2(Y_i) = the total variance * sigma^2(n) = true variance * sigma^2(e) = the error variance

We can explore this variance using a linear mixed model, given the repeated measures for the athletes.

fit_lmer <- lmer(cmj ~ 1 + (1|player_id), data = test_retest)
summary(fit_lmer)

\(ICC = variance.players / total.variance)\)

icc <- round(var_players / var_total, digits = 2)

test_retest_wide <- test_retest_wide %>%
  mutate(test_diff = test2 - test1)

hist(test_retest_wide$test_diff)

Calculating Typical Error Measurement (TEM) and Standard Error Measurement (SEM)

De Vet & Terwee (Measurement in Medicine) suggest that a Standard Error of Measurement for consistency can be calculated as follows:

\(sem.consistency = sd.difference / sqrt(2)\)

This measurement has also been referred to by Weir (quoting Hopkins) as the Typical Error Measurement (TEM)

tem <- sd(test_retest_wide$test_diff) / sqrt(2)
tem
## [1] 1.83711

We can also reflect the tem as a Coefficient of Variation as well

tem / mean(test_retest$cmj)
## [1] 0.1155146

As a side note, sqrt(2) in the denominator reflects the notion that we are using a difference between two tests, each based on their own measurement error, indicating that we have twice the measurement error present in the variances.

An alternative approach to calculating the Standard Error of Measurement, also recommended De Vet and Terwee, is:

\(sem.consistency = sqrt(var_resid)\)

sem <- sqrt(var_resid)
sem
## [1] 1.808038

An alternative approach to calculate the sem (Harvill, 1991) is:

\(sem = sqrt(sd^2 * (1 - icc))\)

sem2 <- sqrt(sd(test_retest$cmj)^2 * (1 - icc))
sem2
## [1] 1.81043

Or as a coefficient of variation

sem2 / mean(test_retest$cmj)
## [1] 0.113837

The same value is obtained by transforming the variance to a standard deviation and leaving it outside of the sqrt() function.

\(sem = sd * sqrt(1 - icc)\)

sd(test_retest$cmj) * sqrt(1 - icc)
## [1] 1.81043

Taking this same sem approach, De Vet & Terwee recommend using a pooled standard deviation instead:

\(sd.pooled = sqrt((sd_1^2 + sd_2^2) / 2)\)

sd_pooled <- sqrt(( sd(test_retest_wide$test1)^2 + sd(test_retest_wide$test2)^2 ) / 2)

sd_pooled * sqrt(1 - icc)
## [1] 1.827228

However, they take issue with this method of calculating the sem because they suggest that it is mainly used by those who are not calculating their own test-retest trial and just using an ICC from the scientific literature, which might not apply to their population (not an issue here, however).

Calculate the SWC and Minimal Difference

Hopkins suggests the Smallest Worthwhile change to be a Cohen’s d effect size of 0.2 (which Cohen indicated was a small effect) multiplied by the between subject standard deviation of the test.

swc <- sd(test_retest_wide$test1) * 0.2
swc
## [1] 0.8

This value is incredibly small and using this approach for SWC it always seems to come out very small (especially if the population is homogenous), so I find it a bit weird. Of course, we can increase the effect size magnitude, say from 0.2 to 1 (more of a large effect).

The minimal difference (MD), as discussed by Weir, is calculated as follows:

\(md = sem * 1.96 * sqrt(2)\)

  • NOTE: The 1.96 is specific to the confidence level of interest. In this case, 1.96 represents a z-critical value for a 95% level of confidence.
md <- sem2 * 1.96 * sqrt(2)
md
## [1] 5.018257

This value is much larger and suggests that we would need to see a test change of greater than 5 inches of jump height to feel that the change is outside of the error measurement of the test. A 5 inch change in jump height would be massive for an elite population.

What about on a log scale?

Okay, before I move on to calculating confidence intervals around each player’s observed score, to determine the range of plausible outcomes for true score, I want to pause and do all of the above on a log scale.

Why a log scale?

Often, we might be dealing with non-uniformity bias in the raw scores. For example, jump height and impulse will different greatly between smaller players (e.g., WR and DB) and larger players (e.g., DL). Thus, instead of reflecting the error measurement and the minimal difference on a raw scale, we might want to evaluate it as a percentage change. The log transformation will help us do just that.

First, calculate the difference of the log performance

test_retest_wide <- test_retest_wide %>%
  mutate(diff_log = log(test2) - log(test1))

Exponentiating the values will put them on a ratio scale and then subtracting 1 gets us to a percentage scale.

## TEM as a coefficient of variation
tem_log <- sd(test_retest_wide$diff_log) / sqrt(2)
tem_cv_log <- exp(tem_log) - 1
tem_cv_log
## [1] 0.1541219

Looking at our tem CV% here, we have a 15% error in measurement. This is slighlty higher than calculating the tem CV% on the normal scale of the data, which was around 11.5%.

Finally, we calculate the SWC as percentages instead of raw values

## SWC%
swc_percent <- exp(0.2*sd(log(test_retest_wide$test1))) - 1
swc_percent
## [1] 0.05155845

This suggests that we need about a 5% change in jump height performance to indicate a small change has occurred. For an elite population this means a player with a 30 inch vertical jump would need to increase to 31.5 inches (31 * 1.05) to suggest a small change has happened. This 5% SWC is, however, well below/within the error measurement of the test, which was 15%.

True Scores

Since we now have an sem for the test, we can calculate confidence around the player’s observed score to explore what we think their true score might be. This works because recall that:

\(True.Score = Observed.Score + error\)

Thus, the confidence interval for a true score can be estimated, as discussed in Weir (2005) and Swinton et al (2018), as:

\(True.Score = Observed.Score + z.critical value * SEM\)

Let’s calculate the true score 95% CI based on cmj_1

test_retest_wide <- test_retest_wide %>%
  mutate(low95 = test1 - 1.96*sem2,
         high95 = test1 + 1.96*sem2)

test_retest_wide %>%
  head() %>%
  knitr::kable()

147297 17.5 11.3 -6.2 -0.4373982 13.951557 21.04844

166828 15.6 16.7 1.1 0.0681378 12.051557 19.14844

Now plot the observed score and the confidence interval for the true score for a few players.

test_retest_wide %>%
  sample_n(8) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = test1, y = as.factor(player_id))) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(xmin = low95, xmax = high95),
                width = 0,
                size = 1.1) +
  geom_point(shape = 21,
             color = "black",
             fill = "white",
             size = 6)

Serial Analysis

Often, in a pro or collegiate sports environment we don’t have the luxury of conducting test-retest trials due to time constraints. Additionally, the variance from week-to-week might be larger than what we would see in a controlled test-retest analysis, leading us to identifying a large number of athletes each week who are believed to be exhibiting a change (false positive).

There are a few options we could consider here:

  1. Use the first two tests for the athletes to determine a sort of “test-retest” environment, even if the tests are a week apart, and operate under the assumption that the variance we observe is similar to what we will see across the season. This was the approach taken above.

  2. Use a few weeks to establish week-to-week variance, assume those weeks to be a “baseline” phase, and then use the analysis of the baseline phase to inform decisions for all subsequent weeks. This is the approach suggested in Weakley et al (2021), when discussing changes observed using velocity-based training (I re-coded that entire paper HERE. This isn’t a bad approach other than the notion that I’ve never seen a real “baseline” training phase in the NFL. Each phase of training has been dedicated to preparing for competitions, so the training demand has always been high and fluctuating based on where the team is in the week. However, maybe we don’t need to consider a true baseline phase as much as we take the first few tests of each player and calculate the weekly fluctuation and then use that information going forward, which was in line with the approach suggested by Bagger et al.

  3. Use a prior season’s worth of data to model the expected week-to-week variance. This is relatively similar to approach 2, just with way more data.

Plot those with more than 3 tests

Unfortunately, this is an old data set and not indicative of how we capture CMJ now (not even the same technology). Over the past several years we have been collecting weekly counter movement jumps on force plates. The data here is Optojump data and was recorded at a less frequent rate.

Recall that we have the following distribution of within-individual observations:

df %>%
  count(player_id) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = n)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "count")

Although the majority of the players had 3 jumps during the season there are a number of players with more than 3 jumps (9 players).

df %>%
  count(player_id) %>%
  tally(n > 3)
## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##       n
##   <int>

We will concentrate on these players as identifying whether a particular test is outside of error measurement and the minimial difference established above. Additionally, we will use the first 3 tests of the entire population as our “serial measurements”, as explained in point 2 above, to determine the week-to-week variance and, subsequently, whethere these 9 players are exhibiting changes outside of that normal variance.

Since we have already determined our SEM and MD above, we need to handle the serial measurements piece. Let’s grab everyone’s first three tests.

test3 <- df %>%

Understanding Variability in our Data

There are 3 sources of test variability we can choose to explore:

  1. Total Variability – The standard deviation of all CMJ tests

  2. Between-Subject Variability – The standard deviation of all athletes Avg CMJ performance (the Avg encompasses each athlete’s own variability )

  3. Within-Subject Variability – The average of each athlete’s standard deviation (the average variability of everyone’s own variability)

total_variability <- sd(c(test3_wide$test1, test3_wide$test2, test3_wide$test3))

# NOTE: Could have calculated total_variability with the long data set as well: sd(test3$cmj)

btw_subject_variability <- sd(test3_wide$Avg)

within_subject_variability <- mean(test3_wide$Sd)

data.frame(total_variability, btw_subject_variability, within_subject_variability) %>%
  knitr::kable()
total_variability btw_subject_variability within_subject_variability
2.77015 2.609481 1.04168

Notice that if we take these measures of variability and square them (to make them variances), the sum of the btw_subject_variability and within_subject_variability is nearly the same as the total_variability.

total_variability ^ 2
## [1] 7.673732
btw_subject_variability ^ 2 + within_subject_variability ^ 2
## [1] 7.894489

We can reflect all of this as Coefficients of Variation as well

total_variability_cv <- sd(c(test3_wide$test1, test3_wide$test2, test3_wide$test3)) / mean(c(test3_wide$test1, test3_wide$test2, test3_wide$test3))

btw_subject_variability_cv <- sd(test3_wide$Avg) / mean(test3_wide$Avg)

within_subject_variability_cv <- mean(test3_wide$Sd) / mean(c(test3_wide$test1, test3_wide$test2, test3_wide$test3))

data.frame(total_variability_cv, btw_subject_variability_cv, within_subject_variability_cv) %>%
  knitr::kable()
total_variability_cv btw_subject_variability_cv within_subject_variability_cv

Partitioning variability using repeated measures ANOVA

First, to conduct this analysis, we need to make sure the player_id and the test_num variables are factor levels instead of numeric, since we don’t want the model to see them as continuous variables. I’ll also explicity set the factor levels of the test_num variable since the order (1, 2, 3) might matter here.

test3 <- test3 %>%
  mutate(player_id = as.factor(player_id),
         test_num = as.factor(test_num),
         test_num = factor(test_num, levels = c("1", "2", "3")))

Now conduct a repeated measures ANOVA

repeat_aov <- aov(cmj ~ test_num + Error(player_id), data = test3)
summary(repeat_aov)

Mixed Model approach

We can alternatively partition the variability of the data using a mixed model, which will handle repeated measures and relax the assumption of sphericity that a repeated measures ANOVA has.

repeat_lmer <- lmer(cmj ~ test_num + (1|player_id), data = test3)

##           (Intr) tst_n2
## test_num2 -0.296       
## test_num3 -0.296  0.500

Notice that the standard deviations from our repeated measures are very close to what we observed with our crude measures of variability above.

Our random effects standard deviation for player_id intercept is 2.52, which is close to the btw_subject_variability, which was 2.77. The residual standard deviation of our random effect (which is often referred to as the “within subject variability” of a mixed model) is 1.162, which is close to 1.042, which we calculated as a crude measure of within_subject_variability above. The subtle differences here are due to the fact that the some of the variability is shared/borrowed/pooled across the population with the fixed effects (essentially, the value of a mixed model and why I consider it to be a sort of “bridge” to Bayesian analysis).

Another thing to be mindful of is that, because we have a random intercept the random effects represent the between and within (residual) standard deviation of the intercept. The fixed effect intercept represents the mean response in the population. Consequently, a coefficient of variation for between and within subject can be calculated by dividing the respective random effects by the intercept. In doing so, we end up with roughly the exact values that we obtained with our more crude measures, above.

# between subject CV%
2.522 / 17.2761
## [1] 0.145982
# Within subject CV%
1.162 / 17.2761
## [1] 0.06726055

The between-subject CV% from our mixed model is 14.5% while the crude version above was 15.3%. The within-subject CV% from the mixed model is 6.7% which is similar to the the crude calculation of CV%, which was 6.1%.

Notice that we can also calculate this mixed model on a log scale and simply exponentiate the random effects standard deviations and subtract 1, reflecting them as a CV%. We are left with relatively the same values with subtle differences given what log transformation does to the original scale that the data were on (but still very close with this data set).

What aout SWC?

As discussed in the previous section, Hopkins suggests that the SWC is 0.2 * between subject SD.

Using our mixed model that leaves us with:

2.522 * 0.2
## [1] 0.5044

As in the previous section, this value is small. Basically, a change of 0.5 inches in jump height would be a change we should care about.

Hopkins also suggests that we can calculate a SWC with the Between Subject Coefficient of Variation by multiplying it by 0.3:

0.145 * 0.3
## [1] 0.0435

Or from the log scaled model:

0.169 * 0.3
## [1] 0.0507

So, roughly a change of around 5% in jump height would be meaningful. I don’t love this because the 0.3 effect came from Hopkins’ analysis of sprinters and determining that the smallest meaningful change in performance to make a podium finish was an effect size of 0.3, which might not be appropriate for other sports.

We can plot the data for the players that had over 3 tests. We will reflect the MD as a grey shaded region of 6.8% around 0. Additionally, we will add error bars of the within individual variation of 6.7% aronund each of our observed points, to give a picture of uncertainty.

sem_new <- sqrt(sd(test3$cmj)^2 * (1 - 0.825))
sem_new / mean(test3$cmj)
## [1] 0.06813493
df %>%
  group_by(player_id) %>%
  mutate(test_num = row_number(),
         max_test = max(test_num)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(max_test > 3) %>%
  group_by(player_id) %>%
  mutate(pct_change = (cmj - lag(cmj)) / lag(cmj),
         flag = ifelse(abs(pct_change) > 0.068, "flag", "no flag")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = test_num, y = pct_change)) +
  geom_rect(aes(ymin = 0 - 0.068, ymax = 0 + 0.068),
            xmin = 0,
            xmax = Inf,
            fill = "light grey",
            alpha = 0.4) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0,

                size = 1.1,

             aes(color = flag)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent_format(accuracy = 0.1)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("flag" = "red", "no flag" = "black", na.value = "black")) +

Alternatively, we can alternatively flag players using the test-retest analysis. Let’s apply those flags to this group of 9 athletes. On the log scale, we found that swc_percent = 0.052 so we will use 5% to flag players. We will also add a flag that is only triggered when the player has a change that is larger than the tem_cv_log which was our TEM as a CV% from the log scale, which was 15%.

To show the effect of using these different approaches we will count the times that the different flag approaches aggered or not.

df %>%
  group_by(player_id) %>%
  mutate(test_num = row_number(),
         max_test = max(test_num)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(max_test > 3) %>%
  group_by(player_id) %>%
  mutate(pct_change = (cmj - lag(cmj)) / lag(cmj),
         flag_serial = ifelse(abs(pct_change) > 0.068, "flag", "no flag"),
         flag_swc_pct = ifelse(abs(pct_change) > 0.05, "flag", "no flag"),
         flag_tem_pct = ifelse(abs(pct_change) > 0.154, "flag", "no flag")) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(!is.na(pct_change)) %>%
  count(flag_serial, flag_swc_pct, flag_tem_pct)
## # A tibble: 4 × 4
##   flag_serial flag_swc_pct flag_tem_pct     n
##   <chr>       <chr>        <chr>        <int>
## 1 flag        flag         flag             7
## 2 flag        flag         no flag          8
## 3 no flag     flag         no flag          4
## 4 no flag     no flag      no flag         13
  • 7 times all three suggested to flag a change
  • 8 times all flag_serial and flag_swc_pct suggested to flag the change while flag_tem_pct suggested no flag. This makes sense given how close the former two are to each other.
  • 4 times the flag_swc_pct indicated a meaningful change while the other two did not.
  • 13 times all three approaches indicated no flag

Paths Forward

There are so many things to consider with all this stuff and I feel like the more I write it all out the less I know because I realize there are all of these bottlenecks and assumptions that people seem to just hand wave over when they publish a paper.

A nice path forward would be to make this approach Bayesian where we can estimate a posterior distribution for each player and then express the amount/mass of that distribution that is exceeding the minimal change/SWC to help the pracitioners calibrate their sense of tolerance for risk and perhaps have meaningful discussions about when/if it is time to intervene on a player’s physical preparation.
